Essential oils are complex mixtures of volatile components produced by the plant
secondary metabolism and consist mainly of monoterpenes and sesquiterpenes and, to a minor
extent, of aromatic and aliphatic compounds. They are exploited in several ﬁelds such as perfumery,
food, pharmaceutics, and cosmetics. Essential oils have long-standing uses in the treatment of
infectious diseases and parasitosis in humans and animals. In this regard, their therapeutic potential
against human African trypanosomiasis (HAT) has not been fully explored. In the present work,
